    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>The \"Build\" is a process that covers all the steps required to create a \"deliverable\" of your software. In the Java world, this typically includes:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Generating sources (sometimes).</li>\n<li>Compiling sources.</li>\n<li>Compiling test sources.</li>\n<li>Executing tests (unit tests, integration tests, etc).</li>\n<li>Packaging (into jar, war, ejb-jar, ear).</li>\n<li>Running health checks (static analyzers like Checkstyle, Findbugs, PMD, test coverage, etc).</li>\n<li>Generating reports.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>So as you can see, compiling is only a (small) part of the build (and the best practice is to fully automate all the steps with tools like Maven or Ant and to run the build continuously which is known as <a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/continuousIntegration.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Continuous Integration</a>).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1875874,
      "reputation" : 75425,
      "user_id" : 1697099,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/gerXo.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Premraj",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1697099/premraj"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 10,
    "last_activity_date" : 1523970307,
    "last_edit_date" : 1523970307,
    "creation_date" : 1473468135,
    "answer_id" : 39421424,
    "question_id" : 2650168,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<ul>\n<li><strong>Build</strong> is a compiled version of a program.  </li>\n<li><strong>Compile</strong> means, convert (a program) into a machine-code or lower-level form in which the program can be executed. </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>In Java</strong>: Build is a Life cycle contains sequence of named phases.  </p>\n\n<p>for example: maven it has three build life cycles, the following one is <code>default</code> build life cycle.</p>\n\n<pre><code>◾validate - validate the project is correct and all necessary information is available\n◾compile - compile the source code of the project\n◾test - test the compiled source code using a suitable unit testing framework. These tests should not require the code be packaged or deployed\n◾package - take the compiled code and package it in its distributable format, such as a JAR.\n◾integration-test - process and deploy the package if necessary into an environment where integration tests can be run\n◾verify - run any checks to verify the package is valid and meets quality criteria\n◾install - install the package into the local repository, for use as a dependency in other projects locally\n◾deploy - done in an integration or release environment, copies the final package to the remote repository for sharing with other developers and projects.\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 16292757,
      "reputation" : 304,
      "user_id" : 11765842,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-qwscrT84hYU/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAANg/_FDe1BJ4GJI/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Sam",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/11765842/sam"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1575969134,
    "creation_date" : 1575969134,
    "answer_id" : 59263712,
    "question_id" : 2650168,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Eclipse and IntelliJ, the build process consist of the following steps:\ncleaning the previous packages,\nvalidate, \ncompile, \ntest, \npackage,<br>\nintegration, \nverify, \ninstall, \ndeploy. </p>\n"
  } ],
